The word is frequently restricted to seli-evident propositions, whether common to all sciences, or peculiar to some particular science. Thus Chauvin in his Lexicon Philosophicum defines an Arriom as ‘sententia generalis cuilibet attendenti nota,' and we commonly spealr of truths, which require no proof, as ‘axiomatie’

Newton’s use of the word appears to be less general than that of Bacon. Though he does not restrict it to sels-evident propositions, or to those truths which are common to all sciences, he appears to use it exclusirely of the first principles of any particular science. Thus, in the Principia, he speaks of the ‘ Axiomata sive Leges Motus,' and at the beginning oi the Optics he enumeratas five Axioms, such as that ‘The Angles of Reiiexion and Rehaction lie in one and the same Plane with the angle of Incidence‚' ‘The Angle of Reilexion is equal to the Angle oi Incidence‚' etc. These would answer to the ‘Axiomata Generalissima’ of Bacon.

We have seen that Cicero proposes the word ‘pronuntiatum’ as a translation os ἀξίωμα in its more general sense, when used as the equi· valent ol proposition. The words ‘maxim’ ‘principle,’ or ‘dignitas' sometimes replace it in its more restricted senses.

The student will find a long note on the etymology and meaning of the word ‘Axium’ in Hamilton’s edition of Reid, pp. 764-6. ³·
